Headlines.Author: Aaron Elstein
Headlines.Headline:
Tech Shares Close
Weak Once Again,
But Blue Chips Rise

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Amazon.com
 and other Internet
shares tumbled Friday, dragging down the Nasdaq Composite Index to another
weak finish. But blue-chip stocks closed modestly higher.The Nasdaq composite fell 91.50 points, or 2.3%, to 3845.34, extending
Thursday's fall of 127.17 points. Selling pressure, triggered in large part
by concerns about the
financial condition
 of Internet bellwether Amazon.com, intensified late Friday.The Dow Jones Industrial Average closed up 28.63 points to 10404.75,
coming off the previous session's 121.62-point drop.Other major indexes also finished lower. The Standard & Poor's
500-stock index slipped 10.69 to 1441.49, and the New York Stock Exchange
Composite Index dropped 1.58 to 639.96.Amazon.com shares tumbled 8 1/8, or 19%, to 33 7/8 after a Lehman
Brothers analyst described the online retailer's credit as "extremely weak
and deteriorating." The analyst said the credit risk is not priced into
Amazon's convertible bonds and advised investors to "avoid the securities."
Analysts at Morgan Stanley Dean Witter and Robertson Stephens also
cautioned investors about the stock Friday.Ebay
 was also weaker, dropping 4
5/16, or 7%, to 53 7/8 after an analyst at W.R. Hambrecht & Co. lowered
his investment rating on the stock. He cited an impending seasonal slowdown
at the online auctioneer.The Dow Jones Composite Internet Index fell 5.1%. Among the sector's
decliners were Yahoo
!, America Online
, CMGI
 and Excite at Home
.Amid the turmoil in Internet-related stocks, investors sought safety in
such Dow industrials as Alcoa
, up 1 1/8 to 30 1/4, and
McDonald's
, up 1 3/16 to 32
5/8.Traders said the weakness in tech stocks Friday was exacerbated as many
investors elected to stay on the sidelines. "Today is the first weekend of
summer, and there's just not a lot of action," said Steven Kroll, managing
director at Monness, Crespi & Hardt. "So when stocks fall, there aren't
many buyers to bid them back up."Additionally, investors are awaiting next week's meeting of Federal
Reserve policy makers to discuss the direction of interest rates. Most Wall
Street firms expect the Fed to leave rates unchanged, though it may raise
rates in August."All eyes are on the meeting, and there isn't much today to divert
anyone's attention from that," said Kent Engelke, market strategist at
Anderson & Strudwick. "Assuming there's no rate increase, companies
will soon start reporting earnings, and that may help the market break out
of the ranges it has been confined to lately."Uncertainty over interest rates, along with warnings of disappointing
earnings from such companies as Honeywell
, kept stocks in a narrow
range this week. For the week, the Dow industrials closed down 0.5%, and
the Nasdaq composite dropped 0.4%. The industrials are off 11% from their
high this year, and the Nasdaq is down 24% from its high set in March.Semiconductors, among the market's strongest performers of late, were a
bright spot among tech stocks Friday.Rambus
 jumped 17 9/16 to 114 11/16
after the chip-maker said that Hitachi
 agreed to settle
patent-infringement lawsuits that Rambus filed in connection with its
high-speed memory-chip technology. The company said the pact calls for
Hitachi to pay an undisclosed settlement fee and quarterly royalty
payments.Micron Technology
 rose 1 1/8 to 88
after the chip-maker posted net income late Thursday that handily beat
estimate for its fiscal third quarter and delivered an upbeat outlook.
Intel
 shares were higher.Biotechnology stocks continued their recent rally. Human Genome Sciences
 added 12 3/8
to 145 3/8 after the company said it would begin testing on humans a
protein that could treat immune-system disorders.Kroger
 added 1 5/16 to 22 after
the company said it ended plans to buy 74 Winn-Dixie
 stores in Texas and
Oklahoma after the Federal Trade Commission rejected the deal. Kroger said
the termination won't affect earnings.In major U.S. market action:Stocks traded
mostly lower
. On the Big Board, where 840 million shares traded, 1,593 stocks
declined and 1,215 advanced. On the Nasdaq, 1.36 billion shares traded
hands.Bonds retreated
. The 10-year Treasury note fell nearly 5/8 of a point, or $6.25 for
a $1,000 bond. Its yield rose to 6.185%. The 30-year bond was down one full
point, and yielded 6.036%.The dollar was
higher
. It traded at 93.68 cents to the euro and 104.60 yen to the dollar,
compared with 93.76 cents and 104.32 yen late Thursday in New York.Write
to
 Aaron Elstein at:
aaron.elstein@wsj.com
